				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Yes, you're free to include other files with code in them. Extension doesn't matter to NESASM except to find the file with that exact name. Keeping .asm or .somethingconsistent might be worth it if you are using a text editor with syntax highlighting, though.<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp;.include &quot;othercode.txt&quot;</div><br />is fine. All labels will be read etc, it basically treats it as if everything in &quot;othercode.txt&quot; was placed where the .include line for &quot;othercode.txt&quot; is in the other file.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
